</description><dc:creator xmlns:dc="http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/">Maho Arita</dc:creator><guid>https://mariadb.com/kb/en/switch-over-at-a-database-level/+comments/1565</guid></item><item><title>Re: Switch over at a database level</title><link>https://mariadb.com/kb/en/switch-over-at-a-database-level/+comments/1561</link><description>&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.digitalocean.com/community/tutorials/how-to-set-up-mysql-master-master-replication"&gt;https://www.digitalocean.com/community/tutorials/how-to-set-up-mysql-master-master-replication&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Essentially both servers are slaves of each other. They can both accept writes that will be replicated to each other. &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;You need to be careful about not writing on both...&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;server1\db1
server2\db1&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Or you'll end up with data issues. &lt;/p&gt;
</description><dc:creator xmlns:dc="http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/">Rhys Campbell</dc:creator><guid>https://mariadb.com/kb/en/switch-over-at-a-database-level/+comments/1561</guid></item><item><title>Re: Switch over at a database level</title><link>https://mariadb.com/kb/en/switch-over-at-a-database-level/+comments/1560</link><description>&lt;div style="margin-left:2em"&gt;&lt;p&gt;As long as you're just writing in one database after the fail-over &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;p&gt;I don't think I understand what you mean by this.  &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Can you expand this a bit?&lt;/p&gt;
</description><dc:creator xmlns:dc="http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/">Maho Arita</dc:creator><guid>https://mariadb.com/kb/en/switch-over-at-a-database-level/+comments/1560</guid></item><item><title>Re: Switch over at a database level</title><link>https://mariadb.com/kb/en/switch-over-at-a-database-level/+comments/1559</link><description>&lt;p&gt;You could probably just setup master-&amp;gt;master replication to do this. As long as you're just writing in one database after the fail-over then it will work.&lt;/p&gt;
